Q2.

The following questions are to help you verify that you studied all of the material in the Making Inference portion of the Statistics Notebook. Remember, real learning only happens as you take time to study the material.

  1. True or False. Inference is the process of deciding whether patterns and trends in a sample of data from a population can be assumed to be true for the full population.
    • TRUE


  1. True of False. A pattern can appear one way in a sample of data, but be completely different for the full population. That is why we use statistical inference to decide when it is safe (and when it is not) to conclude that a pattern in a sample holds in the full population.
    • TRUE


  1. True or False. If a researcher was using a signficance level of 0.05 and obtained a p-value of 0.419, they can safely conclude that the null hypothesis is false and that the alternative hypothesis is the truth.
    • FALSE


  1. True of False. In a typical U.S. Court of Law, the null hypothesis is that the person on trial is innocent.
    • TRUE
  2. Thus, convicting an innocent man of a crime would be an example of
    • A Type I Error.


  1. And letting a guilty man go free would be an example of
    • A Type II Error.


  1. The p-value is the most commonly used method of deciding when to reject a null hypothesis. The things needed to compute a p-value are:
    • A test statistic.
    • A probability distribution of the test statistics that would be possible if the null hypothesis were true.


  1. The parametric distributions this course will teach you about are:
    1. The Normal Distribution
    2. The t Distribution
    3. The F Distribution
    4. The Chi-squared Distribution

3.Use a subset of the CO2 dataset in R to answer the following questions. Filter the dataset so that you are considering only the chilled plants where conc = 250. (Hint: Treatment == chilled & conc == 250) > ?CO2 > View(CO2)

3.1 What are the mean uptake values for each Type of plant (Quebec and Mississippi) for plants that are chilled at a concentration of 250?

# Standardize dataset name
df <- CO2

# Filter dataset
CO2.chilled.250 <- filter(df, Treatment == "chilled" & conc == 250)

# Standardize and abbreviate species names
Types <- unique(CO2.chilled.250$Type)

# Loop to get the mean uptake for each unique type of plant
for (t in Types) {
  result <- round(mean(filter(CO2.chilled.250, Type == t)$uptake),2)
  print(paste(t, "mean uptake:", result))
}
## [1] "Quebec mean uptake: 34.47"
## [1] "Mississippi mean uptake: 16.1"

3.2 Recreate one of these dot plots in R using either Base or ggplot2 graphics.

(
  ggplot(CO2.chilled.250, aes(x = uptake, fill = Type))
    + geom_dotplot(color="black")
    + labs(
      title = "Quebec shows higher uptake values than Mississippi \nwhen plants are chilled at an ambient CO2 of 250",
    )
)

3.3 Report the test statistic, the parametric distribution being used for the test statistic (including degrees of freedom if appropriate), and p-value of the test. \[ H_0: \mu_{Miss} - \mu_{Queb} = 0 \] \[ H_a: \mu_{Miss} - \mu_{Queb} \neq 0 \]

# Plant types
types <- c("Quebec", "Mississippi")

# Subset the data by type
Quebec <- CO2.chilled.250$uptake[CO2.chilled.250$Type == types[1]]
Mississippi <- CO2.chilled.250$uptake[CO2.chilled.250$Type == types[2]]

# t test (independent samples)
output <- t.test(Quebec, Mississippi, mu = 0, alternative = "two.sided", conf.level = 0.95)

# Normal output
cat("Original output:")
## Original output:
output

## mean of x mean of y

# Clean output
cat("Clean output:")
